OL,6,FAdam Scott, defending the teenager who
OL,7,Fused the lighter to start the fire,
OL,8,Ftold the court: "This place appears in
OL,9,F(the youth's) nightmares. It's
OL,10,Fsomething that's staying with him
OL,11,Fconstantly."
OL,13,FMr Scott said that his client had
OL,14,Fpassed his GCSEs, was studying at
OL,15,Fcollege and had a part-time job.
OL,17,FHe said that, due to his age, he did
OL,18,Fnot recognise the risk of the fire,
OL,19,Fadding: "When he was lighting the
OL,20,Fshower curtain he thought, in his
OL,21,Fmind, there would be a fire.
OL,1,W h7}h7}j7}h7}h7}                 G7/15
